name.text: Solve the logarithmic equation, giving your answer in exact form

questiontext.text:
Solve the following logarithmic equation, giving your answer in exact form in terms of \(e\).

\(\ln({@x-aa@})-\ln(x) = {@bb@}\)

Note: \(e\) is entered as %e.

[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

[[feedback:prt1]]

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution:

To solve the equation, we first combine the two logarithm functions using the standard laws of logarithms.

\(\ln({@x-aa@}) - \ln(x) = {@bb@}\)

\(\ln \left({@(x-aa)/x@}\right) = {@bb@}\)


We may now apply the exponential function to both sides. In other words, we raise \(e\) to the power of both sides, which cancels out the logarithm funciton.

\({@(x-aa)/x@} = {@%e^bb@}\)

\({@x-aa@} = {@%e^bb@} x\)


Finally, we solve the resulting linear equation.

\({@x-%e^bb*x@} = {@aa@}\)

\(x ({@1-e^bb@}) = {@aa@}\)

\(\displaystyle x = \frac{{@aa@}}{{@1-%e^bb@}}\)
